"1014","1079":"1079","965":"0965","1066":"1066","1020":"1020","0936":"0936","0945":"0945","0965":"0965","Sauqueville, Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","St Saveur, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"St Saveur, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  French: habitational name from any of the places so called, for example in Normandy, named from a religious dedication to a (male) St. Clair.","2  North American variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]}]},{"name":"Saveur","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(1997: 137;2007: 257; 2010: NA)","Americanized form of German   Sauer  .","Slovenian (<b>Šaver</b>): nickname from a derivative of <i>šavrati</i> ‘to walk along awkwardly’. Alternatively, a nickname from dialect <i>šaver</i> ‘cricket’ (the insect)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sauer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Heinz, Otto, Achim, Dieter, Erwin, Hans, Helmut, Reinhold, Erna, Florian, Fritz.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for an embittered or cantankerous person, from Middle High German <i>sūr</i>, German <i>sauer</i> ‘sour’. In Jewish families, it is mainly artificial, assigned at random by Austrian clerks. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Poland, Czechia, Croatia, and Slovenia.","Czech and Slovenian (<b>Šauer</b>): from German   Schauer  . In Slovenia, it is in part of Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) origin."]}]},{"name":"Hammon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammond","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hammon De St Saveur was born in 0965, in St Saveur, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, his father, Roger de Saint-Saveur Lord de Cotentin, was 21 and his mother, NN wife of Roger de Saint-Sauveur, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Godchilde de Saint-Saveur."},"et":{"965–":"0965–Surnud","0965–Male":"0965–Surnud","0965–Female":"0965–Surnud","1020–1079":"1020–1079","0945–1014":"0945–1014","0936–1066":"0936–1066","1014":"1014","1079":"1079","965":"0965","1066":"1066","1020":"1020","0936":"0936","0945":"0945","0965":"0965","Sauqueville, Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","St Sa